<BR/><BR><BR/><BR/>]]></content:encoded><comments>http://www.blogtalkradio.com/lawenforcement/blog/2009/04/20/Justice-PowerPoints/#comments</comments><guid>http://www.blogtalkradio.com/lawenforcement/blog/2009/04/20/Justice-PowerPoints</guid><pubDate>Mon, 20 Apr 2009 07:43:20 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Clean Your Weapon! - Apr 20,2009</title><link>http://www.blogtalkradio.com/lawenforcement/blog/2009/04/20/Clean-Your-Weapon</link><description><![CDATA[<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt">Clean Your Weapon!</p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt">Ask any good, seasoned patrol officer the importance of maintaining your everyday equipment and you might get a response like “Do cars need gas to run? Or, does a marathon runner need shoes to run in?” Having clean, up-to-date equipment such as a charged Taser or a full can of OC spray is important, but not nearly as important as maintaining your duty weapon.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>You don’t have to be an expert firearms instructor, a Tactical Commander or even be a gun crazy cop to know how to maintain a clean duty weapon.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Ask any field training officer if he stresses the importance of a clean, functional weapon to his or her rookies, and I bet you will be hard pressed to find one that does not.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><o:p> </o:p></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt">READ ON</p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><o:p> </o:p></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><a href="http://www.police-writers.com/articles/clean_your_weapon.html">http://www.police-writers.com/articles/clean_your_weapon.html</a></p>
<BR/><BR><BR/><BR/>]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt">Clean Your Weapon!</p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt">Ask any good, seasoned patrol officer the importance of maintaining your everyday equipment and you might get a response like “Do cars need gas to run? Or, does a marathon runner need shoes to run in?” Having clean, up-to-date equipment such as a charged Taser or a full can of OC spray is important, but not nearly as important as maintaining your duty weapon.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>You don’t have to be an expert firearms instructor, a Tactical Commander or even be a gun crazy cop to know how to maintain a clean duty weapon.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Ask any field training officer if he stresses the importance of a clean, functional weapon to his or her rookies, and I bet you will be hard pressed to find one that does not.</p>
